      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "No worries, I got a bit carried away with the goblin analogy. Let's focus on the brake pads and caliper.\n\nTo determine if the issue is with the brake pads or the caliper, you can try a few things. First, check the brake pads for wear. If they're worn down to 1/8 inch or less, it's likely that they're the culprit. You can also try replacing the pads and see if the noise goes away.\n\nAnother thing you can do is check the brake caliper for any signs of damage or corrosion. If the caliper is damaged or corroded, it can cause the noise. However, if the caliper is in good condition, it's less likely to be the cause of the problem.\n\nHere's a trick to help you diagnose the issue: when you press the brake pedal, listen to the sound of the brake pads as they engage. If the noise is coming from the front passenger side, it's likely that the caliper is not closing properly, which could be caused by a faulty piston or a clogged brake hose. But if the noise is more of a high-pitched squeal, it's probably the brake pads.\n\nIt's also worth noting that if the",
